Hiya,

&quot;Nina Jeliazkova&quot; &lt;jeliazkova.nina@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; Let&#39;s have a resource, which accepts &quot;image/png&quot; on POST and does
&gt; certain image processing, returning a resource URI, where the
&gt; generated image could be retrieved.  Where should the rich semantic of
&gt; the POST be defined, behind the network-level-visible &quot;process this&quot; ?

What beyond &quot;process this&quot; are you referring to? Because I&#39;m starting to
suspect you&#39;re talking about something more like API documentation?

&gt; How does the client decides where to send the POST command, if it
&gt; wants a specific type of image processing? Out-of-band information
&gt; only?

Well, we&#39;re back to the moniker &quot;this isn&#39;t a REST problem&quot;. Here&#39;s how I
do it, though; I&#39;ve got certain resources as gateways into HATEOAS, and
further resources are documented as XHTML forms with links and RDFa as to
what to do with those resources and what to expect. There&#39;s a small
ontology of RDF which documents the API. That&#39;s it. It&#39;s small, RESTful,
and I can change it at will and with need - provided my clients are smart
enough to be RESTful first, and worry about semantics of resources second.

Kind regards,

Alex

--e0cb4e43d0d187a57004b59de48a
